1586632143_16NS3rBdW9zpLmLSQoD8nLTtNVsRF.body:
there was a time, not too long ago, that:
if you called someone, and they weren't home, you didn't talk to them. and they wouldn't even have known you rang
if you needed to go somewhere and didn't know the way, you needed to figure out how to get there with a map, on paper. or get directions from a human
if you wanted to send a message to someone, and not hand deliver it yourself, you had to write (or type) it out, stick it in an envelope, pay postage, then wait for it to arrive at its destination
if you wanted to play a game, you interacted with people, in the physical realm.
If we start treating our phones like they were initially intended to be used, we'll automatically be giving less data to the machine. cellphones have many 'benefits,' but i don't think we're the benefactors as users.
